  "prompt": "Can we do court marriage in any state?",
  "response": "Yes, court marriage can be performed in any state in India, as it is governed by the **Special Marriage Act, 1954**. This Act allows couples from different religions, castes, or nationalities to marry legally without converting to each other's religion. Here are the key points to keep in mind:\n\n1. **Applicability Across States**: The Special Marriage Act is applicable across all states and union territories in India.\n\n2. **District Marriage Registrar**: You need to apply for marriage registration at the office of the District Marriage Registrar in the jurisdiction where at least one of the parties has resided for at least 30 days prior to the marriage.\n\n3. **Notice Period**: A notice of intention to marry must be submitted to the Marriage Registrar. After submitting the notice, there is a mandatory 30-day waiting period to allow for any objections.\n\n4. **Marriage Ceremony**: After the notice period, if no objections are raised, the marriage can be solemnized in the presence of the Marriage Officer and three witnesses.\n\n5. **Documents Required**: \n   - Proof of age (birth certificate, school leaving certificate, etc.).\n   - Proof of residence (ration card, Aadhaar card, utility bills, etc.).\n   - Passport-sized photographs.\n   - Affidavits declaring marital status (single, divorced, or widowed).\n   - Identity proof (PAN card, passport, etc.).\n\n6. **No Religious Ceremony Required**: Court marriage under the Special Marriage Act does not require any religious rituals or ceremonies. It is a legal process conducted in the presence of the Marriage Officer.\n\n7. **Inter-religious Marriages**: This Act is particularly useful for inter-religious or inter-caste couples who wish to marry without adhering to specific religious customs.\n\nHowever, it\u2019s important to check with the local Marriage Registrar\u2019s office for any state-specific procedures or requirements. Some states may have additional guidelines or paperwork, but the overall process remains the same.",
